  <subsection xml:id="activity-directional-derivatives">
    <title>Directional Derivatives</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the directional derivative of <m>f(x,y) = 3x +  5y
          - 2xy + x^2 - y^2 </m> at the point <m> p = (0,-2) </m> in
          the direction <m> (-1,-1) </m>. (Don't forget to make the
          direction a unit vector.) 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First I need to make the direction a unit vector. The length
          of the direction is <me>
            |v| = \sqrt{ (-1)^2 + (-1)^2 } = \sqrt{2} 
          </me>
          so the unit vector is <me>
            u = \frac{v}{|v|} = \left( \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}},
            \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}} \right) 
          </me>.
          Then I calculate the gradient of <m>f</m>, taking the
          partials in each variable. 
          <me>
            \nabla f = \left( (3-2y + 2x, 5 - 2x - 2y \right) 
          </me>
          Finally, the directional derivative is the dot product of
          gradient and the direction.
          <me>
            D_u f = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} (-3 + 2y - 2x -5 + 2x + 2y ) =
            \frac{-8 + 4y}{\sqrt{2}} 
          </me>
          Finally I eavluate this at the point. 
          <me>
            D_u f (p) = \frac{-8 - 8}{\sqrt{2}} = \frac{-16}{\sqrt{2}} 
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the directional derivative of 
          <m>f(x,y) = \cos (x - y) </m> at the point <m> p = \left(
