    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the directional derivative of 
          <m>f(x,y) = \frac{x^2 + y^2}{1 + z^2}</m> at the point <m> p
          = (2,0,-2)</m> in the direction <m>(1,1,1)</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First I need to make the direction a unit vector. The length
          of the direction is <me>
            |v| = \sqrt{1^2 + 1^2 +1^2} = 3
          </me>
          so the unit vector is <me>
            u = \frac{v}{|v|} = \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}},
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}, \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \right) 
          </me>.
          Then I calculate the gradient of <m>f</m>, taking the
          partials in each variable. 
          <me>
            \nabla f = \left( \frac{2x}{1 + z^2}, \frac{2y}{1 + z^2}
            \frac{-2z(x^2 +y^2)}{(1 + z^2)^2} \right) 
          </me>
          Finally, the directional derivative is the dot product of
          gradient and the direction.
          <me>
            D_u f = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \left( \frac{2x}{1 + z^2} +
            \frac{2y}{1+ x^2} - \frac{2z(x^2 + y^2)}{(1+z^2)^2}
            \right) 
          </me>
          Finally I eavluate this at the point. 
          <me>
            D_u f (p) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3} \left( \frac{4}{5} + 0 +
            \frac{16}{25} \right) = \frac{32}{25 \sqrt{3}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
