  <subsection xml:id="activity-chain-rules">
    <title>Chain Rule</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the derivative of the scalar field <m> f(x,y) = 4x
          + 3y </m> along the parametric curve <m> \gamma(t) = (t^2 +
          t - 1, t^3 - 2t + t + 1) </m> in two ways: first by using
          the chain rule and secondly by calculating the whole
          composition and doing a simple single-variable <m>t</m>
          derivative. Check that both answers are the same. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To do the chain rule, first I need the partials of f. 
          <me>
            \frac{\del f}{\del x} = 4 \hspace{1cm} \frac{\del f}{\del
            y} = 3 
          </me>
          Then I need the tangent to the curve.
          <me>
            \gamma^\prime (t) = \left( 2t + 1, 3t^2 - 2t + 1 \right) 
          </me>
          Then I put these together into the chain rule.
          <me>
            \frac{d}{dt} f(\gamma(t)) = \frac{df}{dx} \frac{dx}{dt} +
            \frac{df}{dy} \frac{dy}{dt} = 4(2t + 1) + 3 (3t^2 - 2t +
            1) = 9t^2 + 2t + 7 
          </me>
          Then I substitute the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> with the
          components of the curve, or I would do if they were present.
          Since the partials are constant here, there is no such
          substitution to do
        <p>
        </p>
          More directly, I calculate the whole composition by
          substituting the components of the curve into the field.
          <me>
            f(\gamma(t)) = (t^2 + t - 1) + 3 (t^3 - 2t^2 + t + 1)=
            3t^3 + t^2 + 7t - 1 
          </me>
          Then I just calcualte the <m>t</m> derivative of this
          single-variable function.
          <me>
            \frac{d}{dt} f(\gamma(t)) = \frac{d}{df} 3t^3 + t^2 + 7t -
            1 = 9t^2 + 2t + 7 
          </me>
          Both results do produce the same derivative. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the derivative of the scalar field <m> f(x,y) =
          x^2 - y^2 </m> along the parametric curve <m> \gamma(t) =
          (\cos t, \sin t) </m> in two ways: first by using the chain
          rule and secondly by calculating the whole composition and
          doing a simple single-variable <m>t</m> derivative. Check
          that both answers are the same. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To do the chain rule, first I need the partials of f. <me>
            \frac{\del f}{\del x} = 2x
            \hspace{1cm} 
            \frac{\del f}{\del y} = -2y 
          </me>
          Then I need the tangent to the curve.
          <me>
            \gamma^\prime (t) = \left( -\sin t, \cos t \right)
          </me>
          Then I put these together into the chain rule.<me>
            \frac{d}{dt} f(\gamma(t)) = \frac{df}{dx} \frac{dx}{dt} +
            \frac{df}{dy} \frac{dy}{dt} = 2x (-\sin t) - 2y (\cos t) 
          </me>
          Then I substitute the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> with the
          components of the curve. <me>
            = -2 (\cos t) \sin t) = 2 \sin t (\cos t) = -4 \sin t \cos
            t = -4 \sin (2t)
          </me>
          More directly, I calculate the whole composition by
          substituting the components of the curve into the field.
          <me>
            f(\gamma(t)) = \cos^2 t - \sin^2 t 
          </me>
          Then I just calcualte the <m>t</m> derivative of this
          single-variable function.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d}{dt} f(\gamma(t)) \amp = \frac{d}{dt}
              \cos^2 t - \sin^2 t 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = -2 \cos t \sin t - 2 \sin t \cos t = -4 \sin
              t \cos t = -2 \sin (2t) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Both results do produce the same derivative. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the derivative of the scalar field <m> f(x,y) =
          \frac{1}{x^2 + y^2 + 1} </m> along the parametric curve <m>
          \gamma(t) = (3t - 2, t + 4) </m> in two ways: first by using
          the chain rule and secondly by calculating the whole
          composition and doing a simple single-variable <m>t</m>
          derivative. Check that both answers are the same. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To do the chain rule, first I need the partials of f. <me>
            \frac{\del f}{\del x} = \frac{-2x}{(x^2 + y^2 + 1)^2} 
            \hspace{1cm} 
            \frac{\del f}{\del y} = \frac{-2y}{(x^2 + y^2 + 1)^2} 
          </me>. 
          Then I need the tangent to the curve.
          <me>
            \gamma^\prime (t) = (3, 1)  
          </me>
          Then I put these together into the chain rule.<md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d}{dt} f(\gamma(t)) \amp = \frac{df}{dx}
              \frac{dx}{dt} + \frac{df}{dy} \frac{dy}{dt} =
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{-2x}{(x^2 + y^2 + 1)^2} (3) +
              \frac{-2y}{(x^2 + y^2 + 1)^2}(0) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{-6x - 2y}{(x^2 +y^2 + 1)^2} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I substitute the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> with the
          components of the curve. <me>
            = \frac{-18 t - 12 - 2t - 8}{((3t-2)^2 + (t_4)^2 + 1)^2} =
            \frac{-20t + 4}{(10t^2 - 4t + 21)^2}
          </me>
          More directly, I calculate the whole composition by
          substituting the components of the curve into the field.
          <me>
            f(\gamma(t)) = \frac{1}{((3t-2)^2 + (t+4)^2 + 1)} =
            \frac{1}{(10t^2 - 4t + 21)} 
          </me>
          Then I just calcualte the <m>t</m> derivative of this
          single-variable function.
          <me>
            \frac{d}{dt} f(\gamma(t)) = \frac{d}{dt} \frac{1}{10t^2 -
            4t + 21} = \frac{-20t + 4}{(10t^2 - 4t + 21)} 
          </me>
          Both results do produce the same derivative. 
        </p>
      </solution>
