    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the derivative of the scalar field <m> f(x,y) =
          e^{-(x^2 + y^2)} </m> along the parametric curve <m>
          \gamma(t) = (t \cos t, t \sin t) </m> in two ways: first by
          using the chain rule and secondly by calculating the whole
          composition and doing a simple single-variable <m>t</m>
          derivative. Check that both answers are the same. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To do the chain rule, first I need the partials of f. <me>
            \frac{\del f}{\del x} = -2xe^{-(x^2 + y^2)} 
            \hspace{1cm} 
            \frac{\del f}{\del y} = -2ye^{-(x^2 + y^2)} 
          </me>. 
          Then I need the tangent to the curve.
          <me>
            \gamma^\prime (t) = \left( cos t - t \sin t, \sin t + t
            \cos t \right)
          </me>
          Then I put these together into the chain rule.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d}{dt} f(\gamma(t)) \amp = \frac{df}{dx}
              \frac{dx}{dt} + \frac{df}{dy} \frac{dy}{dt} .
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 2xe^{-(x^2 + y^2)} (cos t - t \sin t) -
              2ye^{-(x^2 + y^2)} (\sin t + t \cos t) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I substitute the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> with the
          components of the curve. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( e^{-(t^2 \cos^2 t + t^2 \sin^2 t)}
              \right) \left( -2(t \cos t)(cos t - t \sin t) - 2 (t
              \sin t) (\sin t + t \cos t) \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = e^{-t^2} \left( -2t \cos^2 t + 2t^2 \sin t
              \cos t - 2t\sin^2 t - 2t^2 \sin t \cos t \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = e^{-t^2} (-2t(\cos^2 t + \sin^2 t)) =
              -2te^{-t^2} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          More directly, I calculate the whole composition by
          substituting the components of the curve into the field.
          <me>
            f(\gamma(t)) = e^{-(t^2 \cos^2 t + t^2 \sin^2 t)} =
            e^{-t^2} 
          </me>
          Then I just calcualte the <m>t</m> derivative of this
          single-variable function.
          <me>
            \frac{d}{dt} f(\gamma(t)) = \frac{d}{dt} e^{-t^2} = -2t
            e^{-t^2} 
          </me>
          Both results do produce the same derivative. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the gravitation potential defined from the videos.
          <me>
            P(x,y,z) = \frac{-GmM}{\sqrt{x^2 + y^2 + z^2}}
          </me>
          Calcualte the change in potential energy along the curve
          <m>\gamma(t) = 3 \cos t, 3 \sin t, 0) </m>. Describe the
          curve and give reasons for the increase or decrease of
          potential energy along this curve (using the fact that
          potential energy decreases to <m>-\infty</m> near the origin
          and decreases away from the origin, to a limit of <m>0</m>
          at infinite distance).
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To do the chain rule, first I need the partials of f. <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{\del f}{\del x} \amp = \frac{GmMx}{(x^2 + y^2
              + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{\del f}{\del y} \amp = \frac{GmMy}{(x^2 + y^2
              + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{\del f}{\del z} \amp = \frac{GmMz}{(x^2 + y^2
              + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} 
            </mrow>
          </md>. 
          Then I need the tangent to the curve.
          <me>
            \gamma^\prime (t) = \left( -3 \sin t, 3 \cos t, 0 \right) 
          </me>
          Then I put these together into the chain rule.
          <md>
            <mrow>
               \frac{d}{dt} P(\gamma(t)) = \amp \frac{GmMx}{(x^2 + y^2
               + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} (-3 \sin t) + \frac{GmMy}{(x^2 +
               y^2 + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} (3 \cos t) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + \frac{GmMz}{(x^2 + y^2 + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} (0) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I substitute the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> with the
          components of the curve. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{GmM3 \cos t}{(9\cos^2 t + 9\sin^2 t +
              0)^\frac{3}{2}} (-3 \sin t) + \frac{GmM3 \sin
              t}{(9\cos^2 t + 9\sin^2 t + 0)^\frac{3}{2}} (3 \cos t)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + \frac{GmM0}{(9\cos^2 t + 9\sin^2 t +
              0)^\frac{3}{2}} (0)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{GmM9((\cos t (-\sin t) + (\sin t)(\cos
              t)}{27} = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          These is no change in potential energy along this path. This
          is a circule path in the <m>xy</m> plane. The potential is
          circulaly symmetric. Moving in a circle (an orbit,
          really) around the central object, never getting father away
          or close, should keep potential energy fixed, as indeed it
          does. 
        </p>
      </solution>
