        <p>
          To do the chain rule, first I need the partials of f. <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{\del f}{\del x} \amp = \frac{GmMx}{(x^2 + y^2
              + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{\del f}{\del y} \amp = \frac{GmMy}{(x^2 + y^2
              + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{\del f}{\del z} \amp = \frac{GmMz}{(x^2 + y^2
              + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} 
            </mrow>
          </md>. Then I need the tangent to the curve.
          <me>
            \gamma^\prime (t) = \left( -3 \sin t, 5 \cos t, -4 \sin t
            \right) 
          </me>
          Then I put these together into the chain rule.
          <md>
            <mrow>
               \frac{d}{dt} P(\gamma(t)) = \amp \frac{GmMx}{(x^2 + y^2
               + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} (-3 \sin t) + \frac{GmMy}{(x^2 +
               y^2 + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} (3 \cos t) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + \frac{GmMz}{(x^2 + y^2 + z^2)^\frac{3}{2}} (0) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I substitute the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> with the
          components of the curve. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{GmM}{(25 \cos^2 t + 25 \sin^2
              t)^{\frac{3}{2}}} \left( 3 \cos t (-3 \sin t) + 5 \sin t
              (5 cos t) + (4 \cos t) (-4 \sin t) \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{GmM}{(25)^{\frac{3}{2}}} (-9 \cos t
              \sin t + 2t \sin t \cos t - 16 \sin t \cos t) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{GmM}{125} (\sin t \cos t)(-9 + 25 -
              16) = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The fact that there is, again, no change of potential energy
          here is surprising. That means that the distance to the
          origin must never change. This combination of sines and
          cosines must give a path that is restricted to a fixed
          sphere. The distance at, say, t=0 is 5 units, so the path
          is restricted to the sphere of radius 5. What exactly this
          path does on the sphere of radius 5: whether it makes a
          simple loop or traces a more complicated repeated figure
          over the sphere, is, I think, a bit difficult to say from
          the fnctions themselves. If you graph this by computer, it
          is, in fact, a great circle on the sphere, just going around
          in a circular orbit, but again, without computer assistance
          that's a pretty difficult thing to see in the curve
          expressions themselves. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="activity-tangent-planes">
    <title>Tangent Planes</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the equation of the tangent plane to the scalar
          field <m>f(x,y) = 3y - 4x^2</m> at the point <m>p = (0,0)
          </m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The equation to the tangent line has this form.
          <me>
            z - f(a,b) = f_x(a,b) (x-a) + f_y(a,b) (y-b) 
          </me>
          I need to calculate the values of the function and its
          derivatives and put them into this form. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              f(0,0) \amp = 3(0) - 4(0)^2 = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_x(x,y) \amp = -8x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_x(0,0) \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_y(x,y) \amp = 3 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_y(0,0) \amp = 3 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I put all the data into the equation.
          <me>
            z - 0 = 0 (x-0) + 3 (y-0) \implies z = 3y 
          </me>
          This is the equation of the tangent plane at the point. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the equation of the tangent plane to the scalar
          field <m>f(x,y) = e^{x^2 + y^2}</m> at the point <m>p =
          (0,0) </m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The equation to the tangent line has this form.
          <me>
            z - f(a,b) = f_x(a,b) (x-a) + f_y(a,b) (y-b) 
          </me>
          I need to calculate the values of the function and its
          derivatives and put them into this form. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              f(0,0) \amp = 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_x(x,y) \amp = 2xe^{x^2 + y^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_x(0,0) \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_y(x,y) \amp = 2ye^{x^2 + y^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_y(0,0) \amp = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I put all the data into the equation.
          <me>
            z - 1 = 0 (x-0) + 0 (y-0) \implies z = 1 
          </me>
          This is the equation of the tangent plane at the point. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the equation of the tangent plane to the scalar
          field <m>f(x,y) = \frac{x^2 + 1}{y^2 - 4}</m> at the point
          <m>p = (=3,3)</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The equation to the tangent line has this form.
          <me>
            z - f(a,b) = f_x(a,b) (x-a) + f_y(a,b) (y-b) 
          </me>
          I need to calculate the values of the function and its
          derivatives and put them into this form. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              f(-3,3) \amp = \frac{9}{5} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_x(x,y) \amp = \frac{2x}{y^2 - 4} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_x(-3,3) \amp = \frac{-6}{5} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_y(x,y) \amp = \frac{-(2y)(x^2 + 1)}{(y^2 - 4)^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f_y(-3,3) \amp = \frac{-12}{5} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I put all the data into the equation.
          <me>
            z - \frac{9}{5} = \frac{-6}{5}  (x+3) + \frac{-12}{5}  (y-3) 
          </me>
          This simplifies to 
          <me>
            27 = 6x + 12y + 5z 
          </me>
          This is the equation of the tangent plane at the point. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
